  "datePublished": "2026-03-06",
  "description": "A meristem is a region of undifferentiated, actively dividing cells in a plant. Meristems are found at the tips of shoots (apical meristems), at root tips, and in lateral positions along the stem (lateral meristems such as the vascular cambium). These regions are the sites where new cells are produced and from which all differentiated tissues — leaves, flowers, wood, bark, root hairs — ultimately derive. The meristem is, in a precise sense, the generative origin of plant form.\n",
